# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1986-commonwealth-games
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The **1930 British Empire Games** were the inaugural edition of what is now known as the Commonwealth Games, and was held in Hamilton, Ontario, from 16 to 23 August 1930.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The event was organized by *Hamilton Spectator* sportswriter Bobby Robinson after he attended the 1928 Summer Olympics in Amsterdam as manager of the Canadian track and field team and was inspired to create a similar event for the British Empire.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] After campaigning for the idea among contacts he met at the Olympics, he was asked to organise the first British Empire Games in Hamilton.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] Fellow Hamilton journalist Ivan Miller helped with the organizing committee.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The sports included athletics, boxing, lawn bowls, rowing, swimming, and wrestling.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The opening ceremony and athletics events were held at Civic Stadium (later renamed Ivor Wynne Stadium) in east Hamilton.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The event was opened by the Governor General of Canada, Lord Willingdon, on 16 August.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] Canadian triple jumper Gordon Smallacombe claimed the debut gold medal a few hours later.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The 1930 British Empire Games made use of pedestals for dignitaries to present medals to winning athletes, as proposed by Bobby Robinson.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] This inspired the Olympic medal podium ceremonies which began at the 1932 Winter Olympics.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] The **1934 British Empire Games** were the second edition of what is now known as the Commonwealth Games, held in England, from 4–11 August 1934.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] The host city was London, with the main venues at Wembley Park and the White City Stadium, although the track cycling events were in Manchester.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Seventeen national teams took part, including the Irish Free State (the only Games in which they participated, although an all-Ireland team competed at the 1930 Games).
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] The 1934 Games had been originally awarded to Johannesburg, South Africa, but the change of venue to London was made due to concerns regarding the treatment of black and Asian athletes by South African officials and fans.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Six sports were featured in the Games with rowing being dropped from 1930 but cycling making its first appearance.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Athletics took place at the White City Stadium, while boxing, wrestling, and aquatics (swimming and diving) were held at the Wembley Empire Pool, where the swimming pool would be converted overnight into an arena with 7,000 additional seats brought in to increase the capacity to 12,000.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Lawn bowls was held at two clubs in Paddington and Temple, while the cycling was held at the Fallowfield Stadium in Manchester.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Events for women athletes included a debut in athletics; the previous games had women's events in swimming and diving only.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] The Wembley Empire Pool was built specifically for the games on the instruction of Arthur Elvin and had been completed in just nine months, opening 10 days before the start of the Games on 25 July.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] (Teams participating for the first time in **bold**).
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] The **1938 British Empire Games** were the third British Empire Games, the event that evolved to become the Commonwealth Games.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] Held in Sydney, Australia, from 5–12 February 1938, they were timed to coincide with Sydney's sesqui-centenary (150 years since the foundation of British settlement in Australia).
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] Venues included the Sydney Cricket Ground (the main stadium), the North Sydney Olympic Pool and Henson Park.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] An estimated 40,000 people attended the opening ceremony.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] A men's residential village was established within the grounds of the Sydney Showground, while the female athletes were housed in hotels.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] The star of the games was the Australian athlete Decima Norman, who won five gold medals in track and field.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] Margaret Dovey, later married to Australian prime minister Gough Whitlam, finished sixth in the 220 yards breaststroke.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] Due to the onset of World War II, the games were not held again until 1950.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] The **1950 British Empire Games** were the fourth staging of what is now called the Commonwealth Games.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] It was held in Auckland, New Zealand, between 4 and 11 February 1950, after a 12-year gap from the third edition of the games due to World War II.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] The fourth games were originally awarded to Montreal, Canada and were to be held in 1942 but were cancelled due to the War.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] The Games were declared open by Sir Bernard Freyberg.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] The opening ceremony was held at Eden Park and was sold out with 40,000 people attending.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] Eden Park also served as the main venue, while the closing ceremonies were held at Western Springs Stadium.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] Other venues included the Auckland Town Hall and the Newmarket Olympic Pool.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] A 1950 British Empire Games documentary film of the games was made by the New Zealand National Film Unit.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] At the 1950 British Empire Games all the teams won at least one medal.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The **1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games** were held in Vancouver, British Columbia, from 30 July to 7 August 1954.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] This was the fifth edition of the event that would eventually become known as the Commonwealth Games, the second post-war Games, the second Canadian Games after the inaugural event in Hamilton and the first event since the name change from British Empire Games took effect in 1952.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Other bids to stage the Games were received from Toronto, Montreal and Hamilton.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The main venue was the Empire Stadium, which had been specifically constructed for the games at the cost of £500,000.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Work on the 25,000 seated stadium started in October 1953 and the keys were handed over to Stan Smith (General chairman of the games) on 12 July 1954.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The games were attended by 24 nations and 662 competitors.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] It was the first time that the games gained a television audience, when CBC and NBC transmitted pictures to an estimated 100 million North American viewers.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Recordings of the games were also shown on the BBC Television Service, beginning a consistent association between the BBC and the Commonwealth Games which only ended in 2026.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] It was at these games that the "Miracle Mile" took place between Roger Bannister and John Landy at the Empire Stadium.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] This was the first time these two (and at that time the only two) sub-four-minute mile runners appeared in the same race, and also the first time two runners broke four minutes in the same race.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] On the same afternoon, Jim Peters, the holder of the world best time for the marathon, entered the stadium 17 minutes ahead of his nearest rival, but collapsed on his final lap, and never completed the race.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] 24 teams were represented at the 1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The **1958 British Empire and Commonwealth Games** (Welsh: *Gemau Ymerodraeth Prydain a'r Gymanwlad* 1958) were held in Cardiff, Wales, from 18 to 26 July 1958.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] It was the sixth edition of what would come to be known as the Commonwealth Games, the second Games held in the United Kingdom, and the second held under the name **British Empire and Commonwealth Games**.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Thirty-five nations sent a total of 1,130 athletes and 228 officials to the Cardiff Games and 23 countries and dependencies won medals, including, for the first time, Singapore, Ghana, Kenya and the Isle of Man.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] 178,000 tickets were eventually sold during the Games.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The Cardiff Games introduced the Queen's Baton Relay, which has been conducted as a prelude to every Commonwealth Games ever since.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The British Empire and Commonwealth Games, including the opening and closing ceremonies, were held at the Cardiff Arms Park.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The following venues were used during the Games.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] 36 countries and territories were represented (and 1,100 athletes), being the largest number to date, with a significant number of teams competing for the first time at the 1958 British Empire and Commonwealth Games.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] At Cardiff Arms Park, an anti-apartheid crowd protested at the all-white South African team; games organisers responded that non-white South Africans were ineligible as their associations were not affiliated to the international federations.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] South Africa left the Commonwealth in 1961 and next appeared at the Games in 1994.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The **1962 British Empire and Commonwealth Games** were held in Perth, Western Australia, from 22 November to 1 December 1962.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Athletic events were held at Perry Lakes Stadium in the suburb of Floreat and swimming events at Beatty Park in North Perth.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] It was held after the 1962 Commonwealth Paraplegic Games for wheelchair athletes.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Most venues other than the specifically constructed Lake Monger Velodrome, Beatty Park, and Perry Lakes Stadium, were existing facilities.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] 35 teams were represented at the 1962 British Empire and Commonwealth Games.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] (Teams competing for the first time are shown in **bold**).
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Note: The medals used at these Games were the first to have a neck chain.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] All previous games had their medals in presentation boxes.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1986-commonwealth-games] The **1986 Commonwealth Games** were held in Edinburgh, Scotland, between 24 July and 2 August 1986.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1986-commonwealth-games] This was the second Commonwealth Games to be held in Edinburgh.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1986-commonwealth-games] Thirty two of the eligible fifty nine countries (largely African, Asian and Caribbean states) boycotted the event because of the Thatcher government's policy of keeping Britain's sporting links with apartheid South Africa.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1986-commonwealth-games] The Games were commemorated on the UK's first-ever £2 circulating coin, which showed a Scottish thistle upon the St.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1986-commonwealth-games] Andrew's saltire design on the reverse side of the coin.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1986-commonwealth-games] Unlike the 1970 Games in Edinburgh, which were popular and successful, the 1986 Games are ill-famed for the wide political boycott connected with them and the resulting financial mismanagement.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1986-commonwealth-games] In addition to the boycott, further controversy arose when it was revealed that through this much-reduced participation and the resultant decline in anticipated broadcasting and sponsorship revenues, the Organising Committee was facing a big financial black hole.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1986-commonwealth-games] The boycott ended any prospect of securing emergency government assistance.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1986-commonwealth-games] Businessman Robert Maxwell stepped in to offer funding, taking over as chairman; but although he promised to invest £2m, his contribution was just £250,000.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1986-commonwealth-games] On a budget of £14m, the Games opened with a deficit of £3m, which later grew to £4.3m, and instead of putting enough money into the event to save it, the new chairman of the Games asked creditors to forgo half the payment due to them to keep the event out of liquidation.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1986-commonwealth-games] The debt was finally paid off in 1989, with the city of Edinburgh losing approximately £500,000.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1986-commonwealth-games] Several athletes were excluded because they breached the amateurism rules, most notably lawn bowlers Phil Skoglund from New Zealand and Willie Wood from Scotland, both of whom have competed in subsequent Games.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1986-commonwealth-games] Due to the boycott only 27 teams from across the Commonwealth were represented at the 1986 Games.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1986-commonwealth-games] Consequently, Edinburgh 1986 witnessed the lowest turnout since Auckland 1950.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1986-commonwealth-games] Bermuda was a particularly late withdrawal, as its athletes had appeared in the opening ceremony and in the opening day of competition before the Bermuda Olympic Association decided to formally withdraw.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1986-commonwealth-games] The theme of the opening ceremony celebrated the "Spirit of Youth" and included 6500 Scottish schoolchildren taking part in a series of large Mass Games-style Gymnastics routines.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1986-commonwealth-games] The theme song "Spirit of Youth" was written by Gerard Kenny.
[src:1986-commonwealth-games/1986-commonwealth-games] The ceremony began on the esplanade of Edinburgh Castle from which hundreds of schoolchildren ran down the Royal Mile, through Holyrood Park to Meadowbank Stadium.
